Where the pleadings involve egregious non-compliance, they are liable to be struck out as embarrassing pursuant to  r 14.28 and there are notable examples where the proceedings have been stayed or dismissed: Gallo v Dawson (1988) 82 ALR 401; 63 ALJR 121;  BC8802631 ; Yeldham v Rajski (1989) 18 NSWLR 48; 45 A Crim R 1 ; Kotan Holdings Pty Ltd v Trade Practices Commission (1991) 30 FCR 511; 102 ALR 51 ; Munnings v Australian Government Solicitor (1994) 118 ALR 385; 68 ALJR 169; [1993] HCA 66;  BC9404618 . But generally the courts recognise that a wide range of discretionary considerations arise where there is a failure to comply with the technical requirements of the pleading rules: Beach Petroleum NL v Johnson (1991) 105 ALR 456 at 466 . As a result, the authorities show there is both a requirement of, and a justification for, great caution in terminating proceedings merely on the basis of defects in the pleadings: see General Steel Industries Inc v Cmr for Railways (NSW) (1964) 112 CLR 125; [1965] ALR 636;  BC6400590 ; Webster v Lampard (1993) 177 CLR 598 at 602; 116 ALR 545; [1993] HCA 57;  BC9303614 . In many instances the appropriate order may be to strike out the offending pleading but grant leave to amend: Rubenstein v Truth & Sportsman Ltd [1960] VR 473 at 476 ; H 1976 Nominees Pty Ltd v Galli  (1979) 30 ALR 181 at 186; 40 FLR 242 . But any non-compliance will enliven the court's directions power; see generally McKellar v Container Terminal Management Services Ltd (1999) 165 ALR 409; [1999] FCA 1101;  BC9904933 . That power can be exercised on various terms, including terms in the nature of self-executing orders in the event of further default (see 
[36.16.75]
); terms affecting the conduct of the proceedings (see 
[2.1.20]
) and terms as to costs.
